│                                                                                                                              │
│ ### 1. Analysis of the Crash                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ - **Tool:** `opt -S --passes=slp-vectorizer`                                                                                 │
│ - **Symptom:** `SIGABRT` due to a failed assertion.                                                                          │
│ - **Assertion:** `(I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), ...)) && "trying to erase instruction with users."`                   │
│ - **Location:** `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:2663`, inside `BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands`.     │
│ - **Backtrace:** The crash occurs within the horizontal reduction logic (`vectorizeHorReduction`,                            │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`). The vectorizer attempts to delete scalar instructions that have been vectorized, but    │
│ one of them still has a user that is not part of the vectorized group and is not marked for deletion.                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ### 2. Understanding the Reproducer IR                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The provided LLVM IR contains a single-block loop with three PHI nodes: `%phi`, `%phi2`, and `%phi3`. The values fed back    │
│ into these PHIs are `%add27`, `%add24`, and `%xor26` respectively.                                                           │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ - `%add27` is a constant `1`.                                                                                                │
│ - `%add24` is the function argument `%arg`.                                                                                  │
│ - `%xor26` is the result of a complex chain of `xor` and `add` operations.                                                   │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The key observation is that `%xor26` depends on `%phi2` through `%add23` (`xor i32 %add23, %xor22`). However, `%phi2`'s      │
│ recurrent value is `%add24`, which is just `%arg`. The chain of operations leading to `%xor26` also uses `%phi2` multiple    │
│ times.                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The SLP vectorizer's horizontal reduction logic identifies a reduction pattern involving `%phi3`. It tries to vectorize the  │
│ chain of operations that computes `%xor26`. During this process, it builds a "tree" of instructions to vectorize.            │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Identification                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The problem lies in how the horizontal reduction logic handles instructions with multiple uses, where some uses are within   │
│ the reduction tree and others are outside.                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ In the reproducer, `%phi2` is used by many instructions in the reduction chain that calculates `%xor26`. It is also used     │
│ directly by `%add23`, which is part of the same chain. The horizontal reduction vectorizer correctly identifies the          │
│ reduction feeding `%phi3`. It builds a graph of instructions to vectorize.                                                   │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The issue is that `%phi2` is part of this graph, but it's not a leaf of the main reduction tree. It's an external value that │
│ is used multiple times. The vectorizer decides to sink `%phi2` into the vectorized code. However, when it tries to clean up  │
│ the original scalar instructions, it attempts to delete `%phi2`. This fails because `%phi2` is still used by the PHI node    │
│ itself (`[ %add24, %bb1 ]`), and this use is not part of the set of instructions being deleted. The PHI node is live and     │
│ will be used in the next iteration of the loop.                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The core of the problem is that the vectorizer incorrectly adds `%phi2` to the `Deleted` set of instructions to be erased,   │
│ even though it has a persistent use by the PHI node that is outside the scope of the current vectorization effort.           │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ### 4. Devising a Fix                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The fix is to prevent the vectorizer from trying to delete instructions that have users outside the set of instructions      │
│ being vectorized. Specifically, when building the list of instructions for vectorization and deletion, we must check if an   │
│ instruction has any users that are not going to be deleted.                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ Looking at the code in `SLPVectorizer.cpp`, the function `BoUpSLP::buildTree` is responsible for building the vectorization  │
│ plan. Inside this function, there's a loop that processes a worklist of instructions. When an operand is considered, if it's │
│ an instruction, it's added to the worklist.                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ A good place to add a check is right before adding an instruction to the `Deleted` set. We should ensure that all its users  │
│ are either already in the `Deleted` set or will be part of the vectorized tree.                                              │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The function `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree` is where the vectorization happens and instructions are marked for deletion. A more    │
│ precise fix is to modify the logic that decides which instructions to sink and delete.                                       │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ In `BoUpSLP::buildTree`, when considering an operand `V`, if it's an instruction `I`, it's added to the worklist. Later, it  │
│ might be added to the `Deleted` set. We need to ensure that `I` can be safely deleted.                                       │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ A simple and effective fix is to modify the condition for adding an instruction to the worklist in `BoUpSLP::buildTree`. If  │
│ an instruction has a user that is not in the current basic block (like a PHI node in a successor block, or in this case, the │
│ same block but for the next iteration), it shouldn't be considered for sinking and deletion if it's not a leaf of the        │
│ vectorization tree.                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The provided patch for a similar issue (D129191) modifies `BoUpSLP::buildTree`. It adds a check: if an instruction `I` has a │
│ user that is not in the current block `BB`, it should not be added to the worklist unless it's a leaf of the tree being      │
│ built. This prevents the vectorizer from trying to sink and delete instructions with external uses.                          │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ Let's apply a similar logic. In `BoUpSLP::buildTree`, before adding an operand instruction to the worklist, we check its     │
│ users. If any user is not in the current block, we should not process it further unless it's a leaf. In this specific case,  │
│ the user is the PHI node itself, which is in the same block, but the use is for the backedge. A more general check is to see │
│ if all users are within the set of instructions being built (`VectorizableTree`).                                            │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The patch for D129191 is:                                                                                                    │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                                                        │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                                                        │
│ @@ -14015,6 +14015,16 @@                                                                                                     │
│        // We can't vectorize this instruction.                                                                               │
│        if (isa<PHINode>(V) || V->isEHPad() || isa<TerminatorInst>(V))                                                        │
│          continue;                                                                                                           │
│ +      // Don't try to sink instructions with uses outside of the block.                                                     │
│ +      // This is unsafe because the user may be reachable from the cold path                                                │
│ +      // of a conditional branch.                                                                                           │
│ +      if (any_of(I->users(), [BB](User *U) {                                                                                │
